   <text>
      <body>
         <div xml:id="note1b">
            <head>
               <lb/>N<hi>otes</hi> to the P<hi>oem</hi> of the
                                        B<hi>rothers</hi>
            </head>
            <p>
               <hi rend="bold">N<hi>ote</hi> I</hi>. Page 25, line 15. “ There were two Springs
                                   that <lb/>bubbled side by side.” The impressive
                                        circum<orig>s</orig>tance here descri-<lb/>bed actually took
                                   place some years ago in this country, upon an <lb/>eminence
                                   called Kidstow Pike, one of the highest of the moun-<lb/>tains
                                   that surround Hawes-water. The summit of the Pike <lb/>was
                                   stricken by lightning, and every trace of one of the
                                   foun-<lb/>tains disappeared, while the other continued to flow as
                                   before.</p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2b">
            <p>
               <hi rend="bold">N<hi rend="small">ote </hi>2</hi>. Page 27, line 11. “ The
                                   thought of death sits easy <lb/>on the man,” &amp;c. There
                                   is not any thing more worthy of re-<lb/>mark in the manners of
                                   the inhabitants of these mountains, <lb/>than the tranquillity, I
                                   might say indifference, with which they <lb/>think and talk upon
                                   the subject of Death. Some of the coun-<lb/>try church yards, as
                                   here described, do not contain a single <lb/>tombstone, and most
                                   of them have a very small number.</p>
            <lb/>
         </div>
